==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} {{term|adverbium|lang=la}}, from {{term|ad-#Latin|ad-|to|lang=la}} + {{term|verbum||word|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈædvɜː(r)b/}}, {{SAMPA|/"{dv3:(r)b/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{grammar}} A [[word]] that [[modify|modifies]] a [[verb]], [[adjective]], or various other types of words, phrases, and clauses.
#: ''The word “happily” is an English '''adverb'''.''
#* (''modifying a verb'') ''I '''often''' went outside hiking during my stay in Japan.''
#* (''modifying an adjective'') ''It was '''often''' [[cold]] outside.''
#* (''modifying another adverb'') ''Not '''often'''.''

====Usage notes====
* Adverbs compose a fundamental category of words in most languages.  In English, adverbs are typically formed from adjectives by appending {{term|-ly}} and are used to modify verbs, verb phrases, adjectives, other adverbs, and entire sentences, but not nouns or noun phrases.

